      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemical Insight\n\nThis ranking is a textbook illustration of **HSAB (Hard-Soft Acid-Base) theory**. Thiocyanate coordinates through its soft sulfur donor to soft metal ions. Hg²⁺ is the quintessential soft acid (high polarizability, low charge density, d¹⁰ configuration), giving it an extraordinarily strong affinity for the soft S-end of SCN⁻. Cd²⁺ is borderline-soft and shows moderate binding, while Pb²⁺ — though large and polarizable — has a less favorable orbital match, resulting in the weakest complex. The strongly negative ΔH for Hg²⁺–SCN⁻ (−49 kJ/mol) combined with a positive ΔS (+20 J/mol·K) indicates both a strong covalent Hg–S bond and favorable desolvation entropy, driving the exceptionally high stability.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
